  "prompt": "How are septums pierced?",
  "response": "Septum piercings are commonly performed by professional piercers in a safe and sterile environment. The process typically involves the following steps:\n\n1. **Preparation**:\n   - The piercer will clean and disinfect the area around the nose to prevent infection.\n   - They may mark the spot where the piercing will be done to ensure proper placement.\n\n2. **Clamping**:\n   - The piercer will use a sterilized clamp to hold the septum steady. This helps with precision and minimizes movement during the piercing.\n\n3. **Piercing**:\n   - Using a sterilized hollow needle, the piercer will puncture the septum. The septum is the cartilage that divides the nostrils, but the piercing is usually done through the softer tissue just below the cartilage (the \"sweet spot\").\n   - The needle is swiftly pushed through, creating the hole for the jewelry.\n\n4. **Jewelry Insertion**:\n   - The piercer will then insert the chosen jewelry, typically a circular barbell or a captive bead ring, into the newly created hole.\n   - The jewelry is secured in place, ensuring it sits comfortably and securely.\n\n5. **Aftercare**:\n   - The piercer will provide instructions on how to care for the new piercing to promote healing and prevent infection. This often includes cleaning with saline solution and avoiding unnecessary touching or trauma to the area.\n\nIt's crucial to visit a reputable and experienced piercer for a septum piercing to ensure proper technique and hygiene.",
